00:05:07.540 --> 00:05:13.436
So let's pretend for just a second I don't want to monitor the health of the entire coral reef, just this particular row of corn in my garden.

00:05:13.436 --> 00:05:18.014
Now one option would be to go through and count each individual corn plant and each individual weed

00:05:18.014 --> 00:05:20.300
but look at this, that would take forever.

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:26.080
So what's a smart way that scientists can quantify the health of an area without wasting all their time?

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:29.902
For years scientists have used a standard reference frame called a quadrat.

00:05:29.902 --> 00:05:34.974
They lay it down in the ecosystem and then they quantify the species in that particular reference frame.

00:05:34.974 --> 00:05:39.302
They can then extrapolate that and get a good idea of the overall health of the ecosystem.

00:05:39.302 --> 00:05:45.165
The problem with Catlin sea survey is there's so much data created that humans can't even quantify the quadrats,

00:05:45.165 --> 00:05:52.127
